<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In color and optics, an alternate term for <a title="Wideband" href="Wideband">wideband</a>. See <a title="Wideband" href="Wideband">Wideband</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In telecommunications and networking, a type of data communications allowing the transmission of several channels simultaneously through the same cable, usually by means of <a title="multiplexing" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/multiplexing">multiplexing</a>. In this way, each transmission has its own unique frequency. Two-way transmission is also possible with broadband communications, accomplished by dividing a single channel into a forward and reverse channel. The frequency of broadband networks is measured in <a title="megahertz" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/megahertz">megahertz</a>. Analog data channels can also be combined with digital data channels. Cable television uses a broadband network; although it only allows one-way communication at the moment, many experiments and tests are being conducted to allow interactive television, or two-way cable television, which industry experts insist is desirable. 
</p>
